    Potion - A SASS/AngularJS Framework

    Finally… FINALLY! Over the last month, I had a small window to wrap up something I have been chipping away at for over a year, my own custom SASS/AngularJS framework. I’ve been working on it for over a year in my ‘free time’ and I use that word with great emphasis on the word time. Between client projects, open source, the day job and most importantly my family… time is really a valuable commodity for me. Potion is a culmination of years building client projects from ground up, repeatedly finding code snippets for small modules and rewriting code over and over.

    I’ve used other frameworks like Zurb Foundation, Bootstrap and PureCSS.. however none of them really delivered exactly what I was looking for. Some included a lot of extra fluff that just bloated the code and some simply did not align with my preferred coding standards and best practices. So what’s the solution? Well write my own framework of course!

    At it’s core, Potion is built on top of SASS and makes heavy use of a modular approach to it’s architecture. All components can stand alone on their own and all of them can be injected via Angular into any page. This makes for a very light, speedy and customizable framework to use underneath any project or app.

    This framework is certainly still in it’s infancy but I plan to curate and grow it over the upcoming months. Check it out on my Github, or you can install it and try it out for yourself through Bower and command line.

    bower install potion

    Page Speed Matters!

    I have finally reached the pinnacle!

    I have been tinkering with website page speed optimization for years, although never really giving it the focus that it deserved. I regularly use sites like Google Page Speed, GTMetrix.com, YSlow, and Pingdom. Over the years, with an analysis tool like Google Page Insights, most sites I built generally averaged in the mid 70s, maybe peaking at 80/100 on desktop and forget about mobile. Mobile analysis would generally range around the high 60s if not worse.

    Don’t get me wrong, I cared about it and always did what I could to optimize images, etc… but at the close of a project and deployment, I’m generally ready to take a break. I always use the excuse, I’ll get back to the optimizations later.. but of course that never happens.

    Now, page speed and micro-optimization has become an obsession on every site I build.

    As of 10:05am this morning, I reached the summit of the mountain, a perfect 100/100 on Google Page Speed and an average of mid to high 90’s on GTMetrix and YSlow for almost all of my personal blog’s pages. My home/index page doesn’t quite score as high due to having embedded pens from CodePen and some other various API calls to Twitter and LastFM. Those eat up some of my score, but for the most part are out of my control. Every other page on my site scores either 100/100 or mighty darn close.

    For anyone who dabbles in page speed tweaks and enhancements, it’s not an easy task to get there. It’s a stealthy combination of image optimization, caching, compression, and many other micro optimization techinques.

    Google defines it’s Top 10 requirements as:
    • Enable compression
    • Leverage browser caching
    • Optimize images
    • Minify HTML
    • Avoid landing page redirects
    • Eliminate render-blocking JavaScript and CSS in above-the-fold content
    • Minify CSS
    • Minify JavaScript
    • Prioritize visible content
    • Reduce server response time
